{"id":"1902.06813","submitter":"Lennon \\'O N\\'araigh","authors":"Lennon \\'O N\\'araigh","title":"A differential-equation model shows the proximate cause of the glass\n  ceiling in European academia","comments":"29 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We introduce a model based on Ordinary Differential Equations to describe how\ntwo mutually exclusive groups progress through a career hierarchy, whether in a\nsingle organization, or in an entire economic sector. The intended application\nis to gender imbalance at the top of the academic hierarchy in European\nUniversities, however, the model is entirely generic and may be applied in\nother contexts also. Previous research on gender imbalance in European\nuniversities has focused on large-scale statistical studies. Our model\nrepresents a point of departure, as it is deterministic (i.e. based on Ordinary\nDifferential Equations). The model requires a precise definition of the\nprogression rates for the different groups through the hierarchy; these are key\nparameters governing the dynamics of career progression. The progression rate\nfor each group can be decomposed into a product: the proportion of group\nmembers at a low level in the hierarchy who compete for promotion to the next\nlevel a given year, multiplied by the in-competition success rate for the group\nin question. Either of these two parameters can differ across the groups under\nconsideration; this introduces a group asymmetry into the organization's\ncomposition. We introduce a glass-ceiling index to summarize this asymmetry\nsuccinctly. Using case studies from the literature, we demonstrate how the\nmathematical framework can pinpoint the proximate cause of the glass ceiling in\nEuropean academia.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 15 Feb 2019 14:00:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 20 Feb 2019 12:34:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-02-21"}
