{"id":"1902.10003","submitter":"K. Sathiyadevi","authors":"K. Sathiyadevi, S. Karthiga, V. K. Chandrasekar, D. V. Senthilkumar,\n  M. Lakshmanan","title":"Frustration induced transient chaos, fractal and riddled basins in\n  coupled limit cycle oscillators","comments":"17 pages, 10 figures","journal-ref":"Communications in Nonlinear Science and Numerical Simulation, 72,\n  586-599 (2019)","doi":"10.1016/j.cnsns.2019.01.024","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.AO nlin.CD","license":"http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/","abstract":"  This report unravels frustration as a source of transient chaotic dynamics\neven in a simple array of coupled limit cycle oscillators. The transient\nchaotic dynamics along with the multistable nature of frustrated systems\nfacilitates the existence of complex basin structures such as fractal and\nriddled basins. In particular, we report the emergence of transient chaotic\ndynamics around the chaotic itinerancy region, where the basin of attraction\nnear the chaotic region is riddled and it becomes fractal basin when we move\naway from this region. Normally the complex basin structures are observed only\nfor oscillatory states but surprisingly it is also observed even for\noscillation death states. Interestingly super persistent transient chaos is\nalso shown to emerge in the coupled limit cycle oscillators, which manifests as\nstable chaos for larger networks.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 15 Feb 2019 13:47:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-02-27"}
